.TH SIMPLE_SHELL 3
.SH NAME

.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
#include "man.h"

----------------------------------------------
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
The simple shell (-------) is a rebuild of a simplified version of the shell.
It work as a command language interpreter that can execute commands read from a
command line string, the standard input, or a specified file.
Commands are natives from the standard shell and will be called from the same
path.

.SH OPERATION
In interactive mode,
.B myshell
displays a prompt and waits for the user to enter a command.
In non-interactive mode, it reads commands from standard input.

The shell performs the following steps:
.IP \(bu 2
Reads a command line
.IP \(bu 2
Splits the line into tokens
.IP \(bu 2
Executes a built-in command if recognized
.IP \(bu 2
Otherwise searches for and executes an external program
.IP \(bu 2
Repeats until EOF or an exit command is issued

.SH BUILTINS
The following built-in commands are supported:

.TP
.B exit
Exit the shell

.TP
.B env
Display the current environment variables.

.SH USAGE

.PP
Interactive mode:
.PP
.RS
$ ./hsh
.br
$ ls -l
.br
$ exit
.RE

.PP
Non-interactive mode:
.PP
.RS
$ echo "ls -l" | ./hsh
.br
$ ./hsh < commands.txt
.RE

.SH EXIT STATUS

.pp
The following exit codes are commonly returned by POSIX-compliant
commands and shells:
.PP

.RS
0		Successful completion:
The command executed without errors.
.RE

.RS
1		General error:
A non-specific failure occurred.
.RE

.RS
2		Misuse of shell builtins:
Indicates incorrect usage such as invalid syntax or missing
arguments.
.RE

.RS
126		Command invoked cannot execute:
The command was found but could not be run, often due to
insufficient permissions or a non-executable file.
.RE

.RS
127		Command not found:
The specified command could not be located, typically due to
a typo or an incorrect PATH.
.RE

.SH PATH
Specifies the directories searched for executable commands.

.SH ENVIRONMENT
Environment variables are copied at startup and may be modified using
the built-in commands.

